  performancePractice: {
    overview: "In Afrobeats, the body IS the instrument \u2014 dance is inseparable from the music. Performance is a full-body experience where choreography, vocal delivery, and crowd energy form a unified expression.",
    improvisationConventions: "Minimal instrumental improvisation \u2014 the groove is composed and replicated. Improvisation exists in vocal ad-libs, dance freestyle sections, and the energy exchange between performer and crowd. DJ set transitions are a form of improvisational art.",
    crowdInteraction: 'Constant and physical \u2014 call-and-response chants, instructing dance moves ("put your hands up," "wine your waist"), and gauging energy to decide which songs to extend or cut. The performer reads the dance floor like a conductor.',
    stagePresence: "High-energy movement is mandatory. Afrobeats artists dance while performing \u2014 choreographed routines and freestyle movement are equally valued. Stationary performance reads as disengaged. Fashion and visual presentation are extensions of the performance.",
    livVsRecordedDifferences: "Live performances extend songs with crowd interaction segments, DJ transitions, and medleys. The recorded version is a blueprint; the live version adds improvised energy, extended breakdowns, and audience-driven dynamics.",
    whatMakesAGoodShow: "A crowd that never stops dancing, seamless transitions between songs that maintain the energy arc, visible joy from the performer, moments where the entire venue moves as one body, and the sense that the party could go on indefinitely."
  },
