  tempoFeelVsNumber: {
    overview: "Bollywood tempo is profoundly influenced by the tala system \u2014 a song in keherwa tala (8-beat cycle) at 100 BPM feels completely different from a Western 4/4 song at 100 BPM because the rhythmic emphasis patterns create different temporal experiences.",
    psychologicalTempo: "A Bollywood ballad at 80 BPM with sparse tabla and sustained vocal phrases feels nearly motionless. A dance number at the same 80 BPM with dhol and full percussion feels energetic. The tala cycle and percussion density determine perceived tempo more than the BPM number.",
    weightAndMomentum: "Dhol-driven tracks carry enormous physical weight \u2014 the drum's bass and treble interaction creates momentum independent of tempo. Qawwali builds momentum through acceleration \u2014 the music literally gets faster as devotional intensity increases.",
    urgencyScale: "Qawwali creates maximum urgency through rhythmic acceleration and vocal intensification. Item numbers create dance urgency through dense percussion. Ghazal creates emotional urgency at minimal tempo through poetic and vocal intensity.",
    comparisonToSameBPM: "Bollywood at 110 BPM is denser, more melodically complex, and more emotionally loaded than Western pop at 110 BPM. The tala framework, raga-based melody, and film-narrative emotional context create a listening experience that transcends tempo comparison."
  },
